 religion, culture and history that were closer to their lived understandings. The figure of the audacious raconteur does not only hover in an archive but suffuses everyday life. Underlying it all, the personal interactions with the descendants of narrators that Prasad tracked down give weight to her innovative argument that the audacious raconteur is a necessary ethical and artistic figure in human experience.Thanks to generous funding from Duke University, the ebook editions of this book are available as Open Access volumes from Cornell Open (cornellopen.org) and other repositories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aImperialism in literature. 0aLiterature and societyzIndiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aLiterature and societyzIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezIndiaxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezIndiaxHistoryy20th century. 0aStorytellingxPolitical aspectszIndia. 4aAsian Studies. 4aHistory. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Storytelling.2bisacsh  aImperialism, colonial modernity, Storytelling/Narrative, Oral history, Native scholar.1 aLiberata de Souza, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaju, P. V. Ramaswami, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSastri, S. M. Natesa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVenkataswami, M. N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2020z9783110704655o